Deceased","1090":"1090","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","0990":"0990","between 1010 and 1020":"from 1010 to 1020","1010":"1010","about 1038":"about 1038","1063":"1063","0967":"0967","1040":"1040","0968":"0968","Mayenne, Maine, Pays de la Loire, France":"Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France","Estouteville, Normandy, France":"Estouteville, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert d'Estouteville II was born from 1010 to 1020, in Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France, his father, Estout d'Estouteville I, was 53 and his mother, Alix de Meulan de Verdun, was 54. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1090, in Estouteville, Normandy, France."},"et":{"between 1010 and 1020–1090":"1010 kuni 1020–1090","0990–1063":"0990–1063","1010–1090":"1010–1090","1040–1106":"1040–1106","0968–1038":"0968–1038","0967–Female":"0967–Surnud","1090":"1090","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","0990":"0990","between 1010 and 1020":"1010 kuni 1020","1010":"1010","about 1038":"umbes 1038","1063":"1063","0967":"0967","